                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Post Homerum, Arma Virumq[ue] canit diuinum ingenium Romanum; ex ipsius Julij, et Augusti vivida, pra[e]potentiq[ue] praxe perpolitum. 
                        Post illud divinum, ecc&egrave; Liuius, tam profundus politicus, qu&agrave;m eloquens Historicus; et cert&egrave; actionum humanarum in 
                        vtroq[ue] genere, tam civili, qu&agrave;m militari singularis Auctor: nec quicq[uam] in polemicis supr&agrave;, praeter ipsum Ca[e]sarem; 
                        nec in pragmaticis, pra[e]ter Tacitum. Duces addant Ca[e]sari Vegetium, et Frontinum: Iurisconsulti Tacito, Durandum, et Bartholi Distinctiones. 
                        Nullum efficacius, aut potentius magisterium; post divina Bibliorum miracula. Sed illa extraordinaria, et &egrave; caelo: haec ordinaria, et &egrave; mundo.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Homer"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Tacitus"/>
                    <person name="Vegetius"/>
                    <person name="Frontinus"/>
                    <person name="Guillaume Durand"/>
                    <person name="Bartolus de Saxoferrato"/>
                    <book title="Bible"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>After Homer, the divine Roman talent ‘sings of arms and the man’, which was perfected by the lively, outstandingly powerful policy of 
                Julius himself and Augustus. After this divine mind, look there was Livy, equally thorough a politician as eloquent an historian, and surely a 
                unique writer about human actions of both civil and military kind. For there is nothing better about military matters, except for Caesar himself; 
                nor on pragmatic issues, except for Tacitus. Leaders should add Vegetius and Frontinus to Caesar; jurists should add to Tacitus Durandus 
                and the Distinctions of Bartholus. There is no more effective or powerful text, after the divine miracles of the Bible. 
                But those are extraordinary and come from heaven: these are ordinary and come from the world.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
